A good progression is:

docker images – View available images.
docker pull – Download an image.
docker run – Create and start a container.
docker ps – List running containers.
docker exec -it – Access a running container.
docker commit – Save a container's current state as a new image.
docker stop / docker start / docker rm – Manage container lifecycle.
docker rmi – Remove images.
docker logs – View container logs.
docker inspect – View detailed configuration and metadata.

As you continue, you'll notice a pattern:

Images are templates.
Containers are running instances of those templates.
Volumes store persistent data.
Networks allow containers to communicate.
Dockerfiles define how images are built in a repeatable way.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The key lesson from this task is understanding the difference between a container and an image, and how to preserve changes made inside a running container.

What you should learn

A container is a running instance of an image

Image → Template (read-only)
Container → Running, writable instance of that template

Example:

ubuntu:latest (image)
        │
        ▼
ubuntu_latest (running container)
Changes inside a container are not automatically saved as an image
If you install packages or modify files inside a container, those changes exist only in that container.

docker commit creates a new image from a container
Syntax:

docker commit <container_name_or_id> <repository>:<tag>

Example:

docker commit ubuntu_latest media:xfusion

This captures the container's current filesystem and saves it as a new image.

Image naming convention
Docker images are usually named as:

repository:tag

Examples:

ubuntu:latest
nginx:1.27
media:xfusion

Useful Docker commands
Check running containers:

docker ps

List images:

docker images

Create an image from a container:

docker commit <container> <image:tag>
When to use docker commit
Good for quickly backing up a container during testing or troubleshooting.
Common in labs, demos, or emergency snapshots.
Best practice in production
While docker commit is useful, production environments typically use a Dockerfile to build images. A Dockerfile makes the build process reproducible, version-controlled, and easy for others to understand and rebuild.
Quick memory trick

Think of it like this:

Image = Blueprint 📋
Container = Running machine 🚀
Commit = Take a snapshot of the running machine 📸
Dockerfile = Instructions to build the machine from scratch 🏗️
Exam/Lab tip

If you see a task like:

"Create an image <repo>:<tag> from a running container <container>"

Immediately think:

docker commit <container> <repo>:<tag>

Then verify:

docker images

That's the core concept this exercise is designed to teach.